of cohost","cornhub","nihongo no jikan"],"askSettings":{"enabled":true,"allowAnon":true,"requireLoggedInAnon":true},"contactCard":[],"deleteAfter":null,"isSelfProject":null}},{"comment":{"commentId":"1602ea2d-bc66-46a5-843c-09e928f44fc4","postedAtISO":"2022-12-27T02:00:08.564Z","deleted":false,"body":"Iirc for 2 digit numbers x 11, you add the two digits of the number you’re multiplying by eleven, and that sun goes between the first and second digit. 11 x 22 = 242, where 2+2 is 4, which slots between the first and second two. 11 x 47 = 517, in cases like this, you take the ones place of the digit sum and add the tens place to the tens place of the original number to find your hundreds place. 11 x 94 = 1034, if your hundreds place spills over, you just go to the thousands place.\nAlso technically the same pattern as 11 times  one digit numbers if you view them as 11 times “0X”","children":[],"postId":602180,"inReplyTo":null,"hasCohostPlus":false,"hidden":false},"canInteract":"allowed","canEdit":"not-allowed","canHide":"not-allowed","poster":{"projectId":5799,"handle":"Gleam-Oria","displayName":"My Rentorar: Ori","dek":"🔞","description":"Tired AuDHD queer dogkitty (θ∆)  \r\nThings I might post about include cooking, woodworking, gaming (video or tabletop), and occasionally stream of consciousness  \r\nFeel free to ask me stuff! ","avatarURL":"https:\u002F\u002Fstaging.cohostcdn.org\u002Favatar\u002F5799-3b17efca-bdf6-44fb-83fb-b411b05fb100-profile.jpeg","avatarPreviewURL":"https:\u002F\u002Fstaging.cohostcdn.org\u002Favatar\u002F5799-3b17efca-bdf6-44fb-83fb-b411b05fb100-profile.jpeg","headerURL":null,"headerPreviewURL":null,"privacy":"public","url":"","pronouns":"they\u002Fthem|she\u002Fher","flags":[],"avatarShape":"roundrect","loggedOutPostVisibility":"public","frequentlyUsedTags":[],"askSettings":{"enabled":true,"allowAnon":true,"requireLoggedInAnon":true},"contactCard":[],"deleteAfter":null,"isSelfProject":null}},{"comment":{"commentId":"3bb69eb6-623f-418e-9fda-5b7546c690eb","postedAtISO":"2022-12-27T23:43:32.159Z","deleted":false,"body":"I kinda like this song. It doesn't really work as schoolhouse rock but it's just kinda nice to listen to as background music? ... yeah, that's not great. And this would have been a perfect time to reinforce breaking down bigger numbers using addition! 11×15=11×10+11×5=110+55=165. The pattern is easier to see when you show how it comes about rather than just list some examples. But then, I *would* say that, I learned arithmetic *after* New Math. \n\nPedantry time! You don't capitalize non-Proper words in Toki Pona, it should be \"jan Misali\". Literally something like 'the Misali person'. ","children":[{"comment":{"commentId":"9e79fd6c-d020-4519-a3bc-abb3c1804271","postedAtISO":"2022-12-28T15:03:22.392Z","deleted":false,"body":"It's the beginning of a sentence therefore it's capitalized even if the first word was \"hat\"","children":[{"comment":{"commentId":"89203bb5-cf25-46ae-abdc-07fc0fccfd2b","postedAtISO":"2022-12-28T19:33:50.199Z","deleted":false,"body":"I suppose it depends on the rules you use for words being borrowed. Toki Pona doesn't capitalize the first word, and as such \"Jan\" reads as English \u002F'dʒan\u002F to me rather than TP \u002Fjan\u002F.\n\nAlso, yknow, jan Misali always writes it jan Misali even in cases where English would say it should be upper cased.","children":[{"comment":{"commentId":"b1998787-04c1-4f71-9e5e-ac122a07061f","postedAtISO":"2022-12-28T22:01:59.254Z","deleted":false,"body":"In English, when you talk about Shinzo Abe, you write Prime Minister Shinzo Abe; not Abe Shinzo-Shusho or Abe-Shusho. We also write Germany instead of Deutschland. Even Proper Nouns, once loaned into another language, are prone to the grammatical rules of those other languages.\n\nSee also my name changing from שפרה to Shel in English and to 谢利 in Chinese; and in ASL I don't have a name at all. All of which are pronounced quite differently and must follow different typographic norms for each language. \n\nAlso, the auto-correct when I write these posts auto-capitalizes the first letter in each sentence, and it's a pain to fight with it. So there.","children":[],"postId":602180,"inReplyTo":"89203bb5-cf25-46ae-abdc-07fc0fccfd2b","hasCohostPlus":true,"hidden":false},"canInteract":"allowed","canEdit":"not-allowed","canHide":"not-allowed","poster":{"projectId":122681,"handle":"PropagandaRock","displayName":"Propaganda Rock!","dek":"A Schoolhouse Rock! Retrospective","description":"Join @shel and @junipertheory as we rewatch and review all 64 Schoolhouse Rock! songs in chronological order.","avatarURL":"https:\u002F\u002Fstaging.cohostcdn.org\u002Favatar\u002F122681-8c451ea8-524b-4aeb-8f5e-a92d112a1326-profile.PNG","avatarPreviewURL":"https:\u002F\u002Fstaging.cohostcdn.org\u002Favatar\u002F122681-8c451ea8-524b-4aeb-8f5e-a92d112a1326-profile.PNG","headerURL":"https:\u002F\u002Fstaging.cohostcdn.org\u002Fheader\u002F122681-7f756d55-3e3a-4372-8acb-7309f2748577-profile.jpg","headerPreviewURL":"https:\u002F\u002Fstaging.cohostcdn.org\u002Fheader\u002F122681-7f756d55-3e3a-4372-8acb-7309f2748577-profile.jpg","privacy":"public","url":"","pronouns":"","flags":[],"avatarShape":"circle","loggedOutPostVisibility":"public","frequentlyUsedTags":[],"askSettings":{"enabled":false,"allowAnon":false,"requireLoggedInAnon":true},"contactCard":[],"deleteAfter":null,"isSelfProject":null}}],"postId":602180,"inReplyTo":"9e79fd6c-d020-4519-a3bc-abb3c1804271","hasCohostPlus":false,"hidden":false},"canInteract":"allowed","canEdit":"not-allowed","canHide":"not-allowed","poster":{"projectId":7470,"handle":"keiya","displayName":"Keiya the Cyber-Kitty","dek":"","description":"Mediocre programmer, mediocre artist, excellent plushie-hugger.","avatarURL":"https:\u002F\u002Fstaging.cohostcdn.org\u002Favatar\u002F7470-bd8b57f0-2560-442e-b51c-96cf62a724f7-profile.png","avatarPreviewURL":"https:\u002F\u002Fstaging.cohostcdn.org\u002Favatar\u002F7470-bd8b57f0-2560-442e-b51c-96cf62a72